                <td width="436" class="texte">The future of gaming on mobile phone is promising because Homo Erectus naturally likes games.  From the African awalé to European card plays, from the Japanese Go game to the Indonesian congklak, games have always been present in the history and culture of human mankind.  Under the various forms of board games, lottery, video, decks of cards or thinking games, play has always been necessary to child's development as early as the age of four months until his last days.  <BR><BR>Behind this trans-generational pastime lies an inexhaustible source of income.  Man is always ready to pay for playing: to buy a game, a headstock, a ticket of lottery or a token for the casino!  <BR><BR>Today the mobile phone has become a means of self-expression, for everyone owns it and carries it.  And each individual can tailor its contents to its own tastes, and then freely enjoy what it wants and needs, at all times.<BR>This why the mobile phone has all qualities required to become a new platform of varied, entertaining, quality and renewable gaming...  at will!  This view is further strengthened when one looks at world hit games such as Tetris, Tamagoshi, Pokemon, which were as famous as graphically sober.  They enjoyed a phenomenal success even though played on black and white screens of modest size.  <BR><BR>On the basis of this assessment, In-Fusio was born in 1998.  The only constraint was technology.  The WAP phone was offering a slow access at a prohibitive price.  The blindness that surrounded it made only the situation worse.  Many analysts deluded themselves about its success but the market was not so easily deceived.  Customer's requirements are always legitimate.  <BR><BR>The success of embedded games had nevertheless confirmed the desire of the public to play from mobile phones.  Quality was sufficient but no interactivity was present.  On the other hand, the business model was not attractive, and its expected lifetime was limited.  Then came ExEn®, a downloading engine dedicated to play, ultra powerful and light.  Fifteen full-time engineers worked for two years to develop ExEn, which was launched in France and Germany during summer 2001.  At the same time, DoCoMo in Japan and SK in Korea also launched successfully a similar technology.  The point was made that the demand existed on the market.  Today technology has become operational to meet consumers' expectations.  <BR><BR><BR>GPRS and UMTS technologies seem to promise a bright technological revolution?   Tomorrow looks always nicer to those who do not want to accept the present.  As for colour, these network technologies will be costly and take a long time to generalise.  As for 3G, it will be a global reality.  It remains to be seen when.  By habit and by nature, In-Fusio will take it up with its usual philosophy made of pragmatic innovation.<BR><BR>Significant developments are already present today: with its downloadable games, In-Fusio paves the way towards the games of the future.  They will be downloadable. <BR>Will J2ME become the downloading standard of mobile phone services?  Fine!  Then 2001 and 2002 will be the years to have mapped out its future.  <BR><p>&nbsp;</p></td>
